PhysicalQuantities.Name: ELECTRICAL_ENERGY
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The amount of electricity used or stored. The base unit used in NMEA 2000 is the Kilo Watt Hour (kWh) which is equivalent to 3.6e6 J (Joules).

PhysicalQuantities.Name: ELECTRICAL_POWER
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The amount of energy transferred or converted per unit time.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: ELECTRICAL_APPARENT_POWER
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The amount of power transferred where the current and voltage are in phase.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: ELECTRICAL_REACTIVE_POWER
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The amount of power transferred where the current and voltage are not in phase.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: POWER_FACTOR
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: Used in AC circuits only, the ratio of the real power absorbed by the load to the apparent power flowing in the circuit. If less than one, the voltage and current are not in phase.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: LENGTH
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The physical size in one dimension of an object.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: DISTANCE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The amount of separation between two objects.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: SPEED
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The velocity, or length per unit of time.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: ANGLE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: All standardized PGNs seen so far all use radians, but some manufacturer specific PGNs use degrees (deg).

PhysicalQuantities.Name: ANGULAR_VELOCITY
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The speed at which a measured angle changes

PhysicalQuantities.Name: VOLUME
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: A measure of occupied three-dimensional space.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: VOLUMETRIC_FLOW
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: The volume of fluid which passes per unit time.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: DATE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: A calendar date is a reference to a particular day in time, in NMEA 2000 expressed as the number of days since 1970-01-01 (UNIX epoch).

PhysicalQuantities.Name: TIME
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: Time is what clocks measure. We use time to place events in sequence one after the other, and we use time to compare how long events last. Absolute times in NMEA2000 are expressed as seconds since midnight(in an undefined timezone)

PhysicalQuantities.Name: DURATION
PhysicalQuantities.Description: Duration of an event or interval between two points in time

PhysicalQuantities.Name: GEOGRAPHICAL_LATITUDE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: Combined with a geographical longitude the two fields form a unique point on earth, when height is disregarded.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: GEOGRAPHICAL_LONGITUDE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: Combined with a geographical latitude the two fields form a unique point on earth, when height is disregarded.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: PRESSURE_RATE
PhysicalQuantities.Comment: How the pressure changes over time.

PhysicalQuantities.Name: CONCENTRATION
PhysicalQuantities.Description: Concentration of one substance in another, in this marine context usually the amount of salts in water

PhysicalQuantities.Name: SIGNAL_STRENGTH
PhysicalQuantities.Description: Signal strength expressed in dB with respect to 1 uV/m

FieldTypes.Name: NUMBER
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Binary numbers are little endian. Number fields that are at least two bits in length use the highest positive value to represent unknown. Number fields with at least 7 as maximum (3 bits unsigned, 4 bits signed) use the highest value minus one as an error indicator. This is likely also true for numbers where 3 is the maximum value, but there are few fields that have this length -- certainly as a number, there are a lot of lookup fields of two bits length.  For signed numbers the maximum values are the maximum positive value and that minus 1, not the all-ones bit encoding which is the maximum negative value.

FieldTypes.Name: DECIMAL
FieldTypes.Description: A unsigned numeric value represented with 2 decimal digits per byte
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Each byte represent 2 digits, so 1234 is represented by 2 bytes containing 0x12 and 0x34. A number with an odd number of digits will have 0 as the first digit in the first byte.

FieldTypes.Name: LOOKUP
FieldTypes.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldTypes.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation. Generally the same special values for Error (max value - 1) and Unknown (max value) that are used for plain numbers are also valid for lookups, but some lookups define a lookup key/value pair for the maximum possible value in that field. In fact, recent additions to PGNs such as alerts have two bit lookup fields that specify four actual valid values. This makes it impossible to send an unknown value for these fields.

FieldTypes.Name: INDIRECT_LOOKUP
FieldTypes.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning but the meaning also depends on the value in another field
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupIndirectEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldTypes.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation.

FieldTypes.Name: BITLOOKUP
FieldTypes.Description: Number value where each bit value encodes for a distinct meaning
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Each LookupBit has a LookupBitEnumeration defining what the possible values mean. A bitfield can have any combination of bits set.
FieldTypes.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation.

FieldTypes.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_KEY
FieldTypes.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning including a fieldtype of the next variable field; generally followed by an optional DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH and a DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE field; when there is no DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH field the length is contained in the lookup table
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupFieldTypeEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldTypes.Comment: These values have been determined by reverse engineering, given the known values it is anticipated that there are unkown enumeration values and some known values have incorrect datatypes

FieldTypes.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH
FieldTypes.Description: Number value that indicates the length of the following DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE field

FieldTypes.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE
FieldTypes.Description: Variable field whose type and length is dynamic
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The type definition of the field is defined by an earlier LookupFieldTypeEnumeration field. The length is defined by the preceding length field or the length determined by the lookup value.

FieldTypes.Name: DATE
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The date, in days since 1 January 1970.

FieldTypes.Name: PGN
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: A 24 bit number referring to a PGN

FieldTypes.Name: ISO_NAME
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: A 64 bit field containing the ISO name, e.g. all fields produced by PGN 60928. Use the definition of PGN 60928 to explain the subfields.

FieldTypes.Name: STRING_FIX
FieldTypes.Description: A fixed length string containing single byte codepoints.
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by the PGN field definition. Trailing bytes have been observed as '@', ' ', 0x0 or 0xff.
FieldTypes.Comment: It is unclear what character sets are allowed/supported. Possibly UTF-8 but it could also be that only ASCII values are supported.

FieldTypes.Name: STRING_LZ
FieldTypes.Description: A varying length string containing single byte codepoints encoded with a length byte and terminating zero.
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by a starting length byte. It also contains a terminating zero byte. The length byte includes neither the zero byte or itself. The character encoding is UTF-8.
FieldTypes.Comment: This type of string is found only in SonicHub and Fusion brand specific PGNs. SonicHub is no longer produced. The use of the Fusion specific PGNs is no longer very prevalent now that there are generic PGNs for audio/media devices.

FieldTypes.Name: STRING_LAU
FieldTypes.Description: A varying length string containing double or single byte codepoints encoded with a length byte and terminating zero.
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by a starting length byte. This count includes the length and type bytes, so any empty string contains count 2. The 2nd byte contains 0 for UNICODE or 1 for ASCII.

FieldTypes.Name: BINARY
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Unspecified content consisting of any number of bits.

FieldTypes.Name: RESERVED
FieldTypes.Comment: NMEA reserved for future expansion and/or to align next data on byte boundary

FieldTypes.Name: SPARE
FieldTypes.Comment: This is like a reserved field but originates from other sources where unused fields shall be 0, like the AIS ITU-1371 standard.

FieldTypes.Name: MMSI
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The MMSI is encoded as a 32 bit number, but is always printed as a 9 digit number and should be considered as a string. The first three or four digits are special, see the USCG link for a detailed explanation.

FieldTypes.Name: VARIABLE
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: The definition of the field is that of the reference PGN and reference field, this is totally variable.

FieldTypes.Name: FIELD_INDEX
FieldTypes.EncodingDescription: Index of the specified field in the PGN referenced.

MissingEnumerations.Name: Fields

MissingEnumerations.Value: The length of one or more fields is likely incorrect

This message is provided by ISO 11783 for a handshake mechanism between transmitting and receiving devices. This message is the possible response to acknowledge the reception of a 'normal broadcast' message or the response to a specific command to indicate compliance or failure.

Fields.Name: PGN
Fields.Description: Parameter Group Number of requested information

PGNs.Explanation: As defined by ISO, this message has a data length of 3 bytes with no padding added to complete the single frame. The appropriate response to this message is based on the PGN being requested, and whether the receiver supports the requested PGN.
ISO 11783 defines this PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN represents a single packet of a multipacket message.

Fields.Name: Data
Fields.Description: Multi-packet packetized data - 56 bits organized as seven 8-bit bytes, each of the bytes is transmitted in the same order as it would in a standard (i.e., single frame) message. Unused bytes shall be filled with 0xFF.

PGNs.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Request To Send
PGNs.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to prepare the receiver for the fact that this sender wants to transmit a long message. The receiver will respond with CTS.

Fields.Name: Packets reply
Fields.Description: packets sent in response to CTS

PGNs.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Clear To Send
PGNs.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to signal to the sender that the receive is ready to receive a number of frames.

Fields.Name: Max packets
Fields.Description: Number of frames that can be sent before another CTS is required

Fields.Name: Next SID
Fields.Description: Number of next frame to be transmitted

PGNs.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - End Of Message
PGNs.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to mark the end of the message.

Fields.Name: Total number of frames received
Fields.Description: Total number of of frames received

PGNs.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Broadcast Announce
PGNs.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to announce a broadcast of a long message spanning multiple frames.

PGNs.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Abort
PGNs.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to announce an abort of a long message spanning multiple frames.

This network management message is used to claim network address, reply to devices requesting the claimed address, and to respond with device information (NAME) requested by the ISO Request or Complex Request Group Function. This PGN contains several fields that are requestable, either independently or in any combination. Note that there are several places where this 64-bit data also occurs, these are named ISO_NAME and can be recursively explained.

PGNs.Explanation: Reception of this PGN confirms that a device is still present on the network.  Reception of this PGN may also be used to maintain an address to NAME association table within the receiving device.  The transmission interval may be used by the receiving unit to determine the time-out value for the connection supervision.  The value contained in Field 1 of this PGN reflects the PGN's current Transmission Interval. Changes to this PGN's Transmission Interval shall be reflected in Field 1.  The transmission interval can only be changed by using the Request Group Function PGN 126208 with no pairs of request parameters provided. Field 3 of the Request Group Function PGN 126208 may contain values between 1,000ms and 60,000ms.  This PGN cannot be requested by the ISO Request PGN 059904 or Request Group Function PGN 126208. In Request Group Function PGN 126208, setting Field 3 to a value of 0xFFFF FFFF and Field 4 to a value of 0xFFFF: 'Transmit now without changing timing variables.' is prohibited.  The Command Group Function PGN 126208 shall not be used with this PGN.  Fields 3 and 4 of this PGN provide information which can be used to distinguish short duration disturbances from permanent failures. See ISO 11898 -1 Sections 6.12, 6.13, 6.14, 13.1.1, 13.1.4, 13.1.4.3 and Figure 16 ( node status transition diagram) for additional context.

The MOB PGN is intended to provide notification from a MOB monitoring system. The included position information may be that of the vessel or the MOB device itself as identified in field 'X', position source. Additional information may include the current state of the MOB device, time of activation, and MOB device battery status.
This PGN may be used to set a MOB waypoint, or to initiate an alert process.
This PGN may be used to command or register a MOB device emitter Ids or other applicable fields in the message with an MOB System or other equipment. If the fields in this PGN are configured over the network, the Command Group Function (PGN 126208) shall be used.
Queries for this PGN shall be requested using either the ISO Request (PGN 059904) or the NMEA Request Group Function (PGN 126208).
A device receiving an ISO (PGN 059904) for this PGN (127233), shall respond by providing as many of these PGNs (127233) as necessary for every MOB Emitter ID that has associated data fields.
If a Request Group Function (PGN 126208) requesting this PGN (127233) is received, the receiving device shall respond in the following manner:
* If no requested fields have been included with the Request Group Function then the response is to return one or more PGNs, just like responding to the ISO Request (PGN 055904) described above.
* If the Request Group Function (PGN 126208) includes the MOB Emitter ID field or MOB Status field, then the response shall be filtered by these fields contained within this request resulting in one or more PGN (127233) responses.
If the MOB Emitter ID requested is not considered a valid MOB Emitter ID by the receiving device, then the appropriate response would be the Acknowledge Group Function (PGN 126208), containing the error state for PGN error code (Field 3) of '0x3 = Access denied.' And the requested MOB Emitter ID field parameter error code (Field 6) of '0x3 = Requested or command parameter out-of- range;'.
The Default update rate of this PGN is autonomous, as it is dependant upon notification rates of MOB devices.

Fields.Name: MOB Emitter ID
Fields.Description: Identifier for each MOB emitter, unique to the vessel

PGNs.Explanation: This PGN provides the status information of an elevator car. This includes the elevator car id and type, sensors for load and weight limits, smoke detection, door status, motor status, and brake status. PGNs.Explanation: The Radio Channel is NOT a numeric field, it has been observed to contain values such as 9000L1-L3 and 9000F1-F3 (indicating private channels as allowed in some countries.)

Fields.Name: Radio Channel
Fields.Description: MF/HF telephone channels to have first digit 3 followed by ITU channel numbers with leading zeros as required. MF/HF teletype channels to have first digit 4; the send and third digit give the frequency bads; and the fourth to sixth digits ITU channel numbers; each with leading zeros as required. VHF channels to have the first digit 9 followed by zero. The next digit is 1 indicating the ship stations transmit frequency is being used as a simplex channel frequency, or 2 indicating the cost stations transmit frequency is being used as a simplex channel frequency, 0 otherwise. THe remaining three numbers are the VHF channel numbers with leading zeros as required.
